  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, or other criminal enterprises) appear to be legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. \n\nIn the United States, for example, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**, the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, and other federal laws make money laundering a serious federal crime. Penalties for money laundering can include substantial fines (often in the hundreds of thousands or millions of dollars) and lengthy prison sentences (up to 20 years or more, depending on the specifics of the case).\n\nAdditionally, many states have their own laws that criminalize money laundering, and penalties can vary depending on the jurisdiction.\n\nIt's important to consult legal counsel if you\u2019re facing such charges or need specific legal advice.",
